<div id="review_1743177782" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1743177782" />
    <a title="Herman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40706083-herman"><img alt="Herman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606696041p2/40706083.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1743177782?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Herman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Herman" href="/user/show/40706083-herman">Herman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40706083-herman?shelf=excellent-history-books">excellent-history-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40706083-herman?shelf=ancient-cultures">ancient-cultures</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1743177782" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10198554008245614449">Roma by Steven Saylor, a remarkable collection of lives reaching from the pre-founding of the city to the time of Augustus with the linking element of a gold talisman that passes from generation to generation from Patrician to Slave to Vestal Virgin to Politician on and on tons of History here full seasons of a TV series is covered during the course of just one chapter, so it a little confusing with so many Latin tongue-twisting names, that it’s sometimes a bit of a confusing rush through time a</span>
  <span id="freeText10198554008245614449" style="display:none">Roma by Steven Saylor, a remarkable collection of lives reaching from the pre-founding of the city to the time of Augustus with the linking element of a gold talisman that passes from generation to generation from Patrician to Slave to Vestal Virgin to Politician on and on tons of History here full seasons of a TV series is covered during the course of just one chapter, so it a little confusing with so many Latin tongue-twisting names, that it’s sometimes a bit of a confusing rush through time and in the course of a sentence you can move forward a hundred years. What the author is trying is to give a realistic feel of what life was like with immersive stories of each generation how one story is later described as how Hercules killed the monster and bedded this woman who was my great many times over grandmother and that is how I’m one of the oldest families in Rome etc. etc. Or by rape and murder you ruined my future happiness so I respond by enslaving your son even though he is my nephew by blood, on and on crazy stories that are all so human and over time take on new meanings as the old stories are forgotten. While it’s a wonderfully long comprehensive look at the birth and growth of the Roman Empire it’s also at times a bit long-winded and sometimes not all the stories are all that interesting. It’s a work that feels a bit stitched together and because of that it feels a little distant doesn’t really draw you into the story so for that reason I’m only going to give it three stars. But it’s a great book if you have lots and lots of time too read. So if you are locked down because of a pandemic or you were sentenced to 18 months for tax fraud this is a good book for you. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10198554008245614449" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


