    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2600819218" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2600819218" />
    <a title="Gabriel Woods" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/55919873-gabriel-woods"><img alt="Gabriel Woods" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1463428369p2/55919873.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2600819218?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gabriel Woods" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gabriel Woods" href="/user/show/55919873-gabriel-woods">Gabriel Woods</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2600819218" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10144090823144368812">At first I found this book very slow paced. I did not like how each chapter was a different story in the same region until I realised each chapter in the beginning was part of Roman folklore before the recorded history of the ancient city of Rome existed.<br/><br/>I began to really enjoy the book when Cleopatra became part of Roman history. Saylor gives praise and criticism equally to male and female historical individuals. <br/>Cleopatra was definitely a colorful ruler, or goddess as her people saw her. But i</span>
  <span id="freeText10144090823144368812" style="display:none">At first I found this book very slow paced. I did not like how each chapter was a different story in the same region until I realised each chapter in the beginning was part of Roman folklore before the recorded history of the ancient city of Rome existed.<br /><br />I began to really enjoy the book when Cleopatra became part of Roman history. Saylor gives praise and criticism equally to male and female historical individuals. <br />Cleopatra was definitely a colorful ruler, or goddess as her people saw her. But in Greek and Roman literature she is almost just a footnote. In Rome at that time Cleopatra was dubbed the "Egyptian whore" Saylor corrects this and describes her and Egypt in detail. I am very interested in Egyptian history and I have watched nearly every program there is about Egypt. <br />I visited the Egyptian section of the British Museum five times, each time adoring each Egyptian piece, when I lived in London. Saylor captures Egypt and decadence of Cleopatra perfectly in my opinion. The leaders of both Egypt and Rome knew how to have a good time! <br /><br />Where this book falls down is that Rome itself - the most powerful city in the world at one time and still controls some of the world by being the centre of Catholism - for most of the book was not well enough described. The author focused more on historical personalities but the city of Roma was magnificent even in the beginning of it's history. However Saylor corrected this later in the book.<br /><br />A pleasant read and despite the length of the book I read each and every page.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10144090823144368812" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


